&gt; To inject a slightly more serious note into the
&gt; smugness of your
&gt; &#39;leftie&#39;
&gt; members ... 
&gt; 
&gt; Do any members KNOW if left-handedness was extant
&gt; among early Japanese
&gt; swordsmen.  I have never, personally, seen
&gt; illustrations of samurai
&gt; wearing
&gt; their swords on the right side, and it is not
&gt; inconceivable that they
&gt; were
&gt; trained at an early age to use their swords in the
&gt; conventional manner. 
&gt; The
&gt; only advantage in being left handed is, surely, its
&gt; comparative rarity
&gt; and
&gt; strangeness to a right-handed opponent.
&gt; 
&gt; Interestingly, I have in my collection (WAY
&gt; 386.27.ex Gardiner
&gt; collection)
&gt; an unsigned,  shakudo fuchi-gashira, attributed to
&gt; Hirata Harunari  This
&gt; has
&gt; an ishime surface, with takaramono in a shippo of
&gt; coloured enamels
&gt; within
&gt; gold cloissons.  The ura surface of the fuchi has
&gt; had an additional
&gt; takaramono added in gold lacquer, and this may
&gt; possibly be to facilitate
&gt; its
&gt; wearing on the right side by presenting a more
&gt; decorative surface.  I
&gt; can
&gt; think of no other possible explanation for this
&gt; modification.
&gt; 
&gt; John L.
